GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 29
Short Title: Use Tribal ID for Alcohol & Tobacco Purchase. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Clampitt.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Federal Relations and American Indian Affairs, if favorable, Alcoholic Beverage
Control, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
February 3, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW THE USE OF A TRIBAL ENROLLMENT CARD ISSUED BY A
3 STATE OR FEDERALLY RECOGNIZED INDIAN TRIBE WHEN MAKING ALCOHOL
4 OR TOBACCO PURCHASES.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. G.S. 18B-302(d) reads as rewritten:
7 "(d) Defense. – It is a defense to a violation of subsection (a) of this section if the seller
8 does any of the following:
9 (1) Shows that the purchaser produced a driver's license, a special identification
10 card issued under G.S. 20-37.7 or issued by the state agency of any other state
11 authorized to issue similar official state special identification cards for that
12 state, a tribal enrollment card issued by a State or federally recognized Indian
13 Tribe, a military identification card, or a passport, showing the purchaser's age
14 to be at least the required age for purchase and bearing a physical description
15 of the person named on the card reasonably describing the purchaser.
16 …
17 (3) Shows that at the time of purchase, the purchaser utilized a biometric
18 identification system that demonstrated (i) the purchaser's age to be at least
19 the required age for the purchase and (ii) the purchaser had previously
20 registered with the seller or seller's agent a drivers license, a special
21 identification card issued under G.S. 20-37.7 or issued by the state agency of
22 any other state authorized to issue similar official state special identification
23 cards for that state, a tribal enrollment card issued by a State or federally
24 recognized Indian Tribe, a military identification card, or a passport showing
25 the purchaser's date of birth and bearing a physical description of the person
26 named on the document."
27 SECTION 2. G.S. 14-313 reads as rewritten:
28 "§ 14-313. Youth access to tobacco products, tobacco-derived products, vapor products,
29 and cigarette wrapping papers.
30 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
31 …
32 (2) Proof of age. – A drivers license license, a tribal enrollment card issued by a
33 State or federally recognized Indian Tribe, or other photographic
*H29-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 identification that includes the bearer's date of birth that purports to establish
2 that the person is 18 years of age or older.
3 …
4 (b) Sale or distribution to persons under the age of 18 years. – If any person shall
5 distribute, or aid, assist, or abet any other person in distributing tobacco products or cigarette
6 wrapping papers to any person under the age of 18 years, or if any person shall purchase tobacco
7 products or cigarette wrapping papers on behalf of a person under the age of 18 years, the person
8 shall be guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor; provided, however, that it shall not be unlawful to
9 distribute tobacco products or cigarette wrapping papers to an employee when required in the
10 performance of the employee's duties. Retail distributors of tobacco products shall prominently
11 display near the point of sale a sign in letters at least five-eighths of an inch high which states the
12 following:
13 …
14 Failure to post the required sign shall be an infraction punishable by a fine of twenty-five dollars
15 ($25.00) for the first offense and seventy-five dollars ($75.00) for each succeeding offense.
16 A person engaged in the sale of tobacco products or cigarette wrapping papers shall demand
17 proof of age from a prospective purchaser if the person has reasonable grounds to believe that
18 the prospective purchaser is under 18 years of age. Failure to demand proof of age as required by
19 this subsection is a Class 2 misdemeanor if in fact the prospective purchaser is under 18 years of
20 age. Retail distributors of tobacco products or cigarette wrapping papers shall train their sales
21 employees in the requirements of this law. Proof of any of the following shall be a defense to any
22 action brought under this subsection:
23 (1) The defendant demanded, was shown, and reasonably relied upon proof of age
24 in the case of a retailer, or any other documentary or written evidence of age
25 in the case of a nonretailer.
26 (2) The defendant relied on the electronic system established and operated by the
27 Division of Motor Vehicles pursuant to G.S. 20-37.02.
28 (3) The defendant relied on a biometric identification system that demonstrated
29 (i) the purchaser's age to be at least the required age for the purchase and (ii)
30 the purchaser had previously registered with the seller or seller's agent a
31 drivers license, a special identification card issued under G.S. 20-37.7, a tribal
32 enrollment card issued by a State or federally recognized Indian Tribe, a
33 military identification card, or a passport showing the purchaser's date of birth
34 and bearing a physical description of the person named on the card.
35 …
36 (d) Sending or assisting a person less than 18 years to purchase or receive tobacco
37 products or cigarette wrapping papers. – If any person shall send a person less than 18 years of
38 age to purchase, acquire, receive, or attempt to purchase, acquire, or receive tobacco products or
39 cigarette wrapping papers, or if any person shall aid or abet a person who is less than 18 years of
40 age in purchasing, acquiring, or receiving or attempting to purchase, acquire, or receive tobacco
41 products or cigarette wrapping papers, the person shall be guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor;
42 provided, however, persons under the age of 18 may be enlisted by police or local sheriffs'
43 departments to test compliance if the testing is under the direct supervision of that law
44 enforcement department and written parental consent is provided; provided further, that the
45 Department of Health and Human Services shall have the authority, pursuant to a written plan
46 prepared by the Secretary of Health and Human Services, to use persons under 18 years of age
47 in annual, random, unannounced inspections, provided that prior written parental consent is given
48 for the involvement of these persons and that the inspections are conducted for the sole purpose
49 of preparing a scientifically and methodologically valid statistical study of the extent of success
50 the State has achieved in reducing the availability of tobacco products to persons under the age
